releases.title: Op Jacht Naar Vernuft
releases.notes:
This is a promotional CDi given away at the "Op Jacht Naar Vernuft" school project, where high school students of the Netherlands were given demonstrations about the techniques Philips used and the new Philips products (CDi, DCC) at the time.

The CDi section on track 1 contains basic information about the CDi format. The other tracks are all playable on a regular CD player.

Tracks 2 to 5 are songs that were used for tv commercials at the time.

Track 6 is a live recording of a (only internally used) promotional song for general Philips brand promotion.

The rest of the tracks can be used to test your CD player. The booklet gives information on how to use the frequencies.

releases.title: Chartbusters August 1994
releases.notes:
Artist on track 4 listed as: La Danz/B King.



This was the fifth edition in the legal "Chartbusters" series that came out.

The work and copyright was held by "Arty Records" which was quite small and couldn't afford to pay all expensive artists so this legal version of the series "Chartbusters" had started by April (Part 4.) and ended with a total flop with number 9 (September).

Nice fact; they changed their name by the last part into "Chart Tracks". Anyway it was the last in the short series.

Another fact was that from Vol. 7 (July) also the illegal Chartbusters were back, and they were filled with real original hits were was (as usual) not payed a penny for.

The months July and August even had 2 different versions of the illegal Chartbusters.

1 with "[url=http://www.discogs.com/Various-Chartbusters-1994-Volume-08/release/2816246]orange coloured paper-clips[/url]"  and 1 in the "[url=http://www.discogs.com/Various-Chartbusters-1994-Volume-8/release/2929217]Red jewelcase[/url]" too.

Also the illegal Chartbusters stopped by the 10th release.

releases.title: Unfinished Sympathy
releases.notes:
The group were forced to change their name due to the outbreak of the Gulf War in 1991. They were briefly known as "Massive", although this is not the name used on this release.
Just a few initial radio DJ copies which held the original name were printed; they had to be returned immediately to be destroyed and were replaced by a [url=http://www.discogs.com/Massive-Unfinished-Sympathy/release/2150243]repress[/url]. Some DJs didn't return their copies, and so these original copies are very rare.
